      "writtenOn": "2026-04-21T09:30:15Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I am not sure it is safe.\nwe are not accessing it just from netty loop. It is modified in .invoke() from application thread, so it can be accessed from 2 threads. Invoke is used only in tests. \nIt was same for dispatcher logic, it just went trough HTTPClient.invoke() -\u003e dispatch()\nIt could be left like it is or potentially improved by wrapping invoke() logic to channel.eventLoop().execute(). IMO that should be addressed separately.",
      "parentUuid": "dd27d312_65a55b6f",
      "revId": "52561c16227aa18a2c30dd72ef32f9e39f8f7370",
      "serverId": "7fc14799-209e-464c-9743-7a06c2c21a81"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "953f8fb5_f8645dbd",
        "filename": "protocol/restconf-client/src/main/java/org/opendaylight/restconf/client/ClientHttp1Session.java",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 68,
      "author": {
        "id": 8449
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-04-21T13:52:39Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "If this can be accessed from multiple threads, why not make local.writeAndFlush thread-safe as well? In this situation, the queue could contain requests in a different order than they are actually written to the channel.\n\nCan we use something like this?\n```\n        local.eventLoop().execute(() -\u003e {\n            queue.add(req);\n            local.writeAndFlush(request).addListener(sent -\u003e {\n                final var cause \u003d sent.cause();\n                if (cause !\u003d null \u0026\u0026 queue.remove(req)) {\n                    callback.onFailure(cause);\n                }\n            });\n        });\n```",
      "revId": "52561c16227aa18a2c30dd72ef32f9e39f8f7370",
      "serverId": "7fc14799-209e-464c-9743-7a06c2c21a81"
    },
